{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"54f31e7c-9182-4ca4-8615-2ab8b4b63993","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Find your process:**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**3. Collect the trace (30 seconds example):**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n**4. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**5. Analyze** in Visual Studio, PerfView, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app) (use `--format speedscope` for browser-based analysis).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If you can't install tools (read-only filesystem), use a **sidecar** or the [dotnet-monitor](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/diagnostics/dotnet-monitor) container image instead.\n- For production-safe, low-overhead collection, prefer `dotnet-monitor` exposed via a sidecar — it collects traces via HTTP endpoints without exec'ing in.\n- If you need OS-level context (kernel stacks, off-CPU time), use `perf` or `dotnet-trace` with `--format speedscope` combined with `--clrevents` for richer data.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"284c8fb0-1f9f-4745-a463-58fd589c5694","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostics/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I'll provide a concise, practical answer.","outputTokens":456,"requestId":"784F:3038F3:1E9D3C8:21E9E96:69FA990B"},"id":"e314ed16-9ea5-4770-9ead-8f5a12430c07","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:27:51.937Z","parentId":"e9fe4eb8-1b45-48ac-9b8d-64e40f9b0ade"}
